{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Plotting `vplanet` runs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "tags": [
     "hide_input"
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#hide_input\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "from IPython.display import set_matplotlib_formats\n",
    "\n",
    "set_matplotlib_formats('retina')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Overview"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "tags": [
     "hide_input"
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#hide_input\n",
    "# Tar up the example folder\n",
    "import glob\n",
    "import tarfile\n",
    "import os\n",
    "\n",
    "with tarfile.open(\"examples/CircumbinaryOrbit.tar.gz\", \"w:gz\") as tar:\n",
    "    for file in glob.glob(\"examples/CircumbinaryOrbit/*.in\"):\n",
    "        tar.add(file, arcname=os.path.basename(file))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {
    "raw_mimetype": "text/restructuredtext"
   },
   "source": [
    "Let's plot the results of the :download:`CircumbinaryOrbit <examples/CircumbinaryOrbit.tar.gz>` example. We begin by fetching the output of the simulation with :py:obj:`vplot`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import vplot as vpl\n",
    "\n",
    "output = vpl.get_output(\"examples/CircumbinaryOrbit\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {
    "raw_mimetype": "text/restructuredtext"
   },
   "source": [
    "Let's grab the :py:obj:`Eccentricity` arrays for both planets in the simulation. For more details on this, see the tutorial on `get_output <GetOutput.ipynb>`_."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "time = output.earth.Time\n",
    "earth_e = output.earth.Eccentricity\n",
    "cbp_e = output.cbp.Eccentricity"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {
    "raw_mimetype": "text/restructuredtext"
   },
   "source": [
    "Behind the scenes, :py:obj:`vplot` subclasses and overrides :py:obj:`matplotlib.figure.Figure`, which enables it to automagically format plots containing :py:obj:`vplanet` quantities. Check it out:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<VPLOTFigure size 460.8x316.8 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 285,
       "width": 420
      },
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.plot(time, earth_e);\n",
    "plt.plot(time, cbp_e);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {
    "raw_mimetype": "text/restructuredtext"
   },
   "source": [
    "Note how :py:obj:`vplot` automatically added axes labels and a legend, without any input from the user. There is a lot of functionality built into the plotting in :py:obj:`vplot`, so make sure to try it out."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {
    "raw_mimetype": "text/restructuredtext"
   },
   "source": [
    ".. note ::\n",
    "   More coming soon!"
   ]
  }
